text: with the split decision in Tuesday's
primaries North Carolina going heavily
for Barack Obama an Indiana much more
narrowly for Hillary Clinton it seems as
if Obama is moving closer to clinching
the Democratic nomination certainly the
sense of thrill outside the United
States is not abated everybody is
following this contest as they have been
for months now very very closely but
what is interesting is that now as it
seems we're moving closer towards a
democratic decision and we know who the
Republican candidate is people are
starting to wonder what kind of policies
will the new person in the White House
instigate I just came from a lunch in
Paris today at which leading political
business and diplomatic figures were
wondering how protectionist is the
United States for instance going to be
under a new president the Democrats have
engaged in plenty of rhetoric about the
need to protect the American worker but
what is this going to mean for the rest
of the world these are just some of the
questions that are being posed as the
world eagerly tracks what is going to
happen next in the United States this
may no longer be the American Century is
postulated in a series of new books
about the rise of other world powers but
people certainly do still look to
America to take the lead for the
International Herald Tribune in Paris
